{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500457"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:14:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:14:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1647"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1647"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.17,0.07,0.57,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1647"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58575"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1647"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1647"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43977"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2921"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18220"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58575"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents to his GP with a six-month history of dysphagia. He reports that over this period of time, he has had trouble swallowing both liquids and solids, with occasional gurgling noted. His wife has noticed that his breath is also smelling worse than it used to. His past medical history includes osteoarthritis, hypertension, GORD and chronic lymphocytic leukaemia. He used to be a heavy smoker and drinks around 3-4 beers each day. On examination, his vital signs are normal. His pharynx appears unremarkable, although obvious halitosis can be detected. Neck exam reveals no lumps or swellings. Cardiorespiratory exam reveals no abnormalities. Permberton\u0027s sign is negative. Amongst his various investigations, a plain lateral chest X-ray is ordered (Image)).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Para-oesophageal hernia","Carcinoma mid-third oesophagus","Schatzki ring","Pharyngeal pouch","Retrosternal goitre"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is a \u003Cstrong\u003Epharyngeal pouch\u003C/strong\u003E. An air-fluid level is visible in the upper part of the X-ray (Image). A pharyngeal pouch is an out-pouching of pharyngeal mucosa between the cricopharyngeus and thyropharyngeus muscles, just proximal to the transition point between the hypopharynx and the upper oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon symptoms of a pharyngeal pouch include dysphagia, chronic cough, regurgitation of undigested food, gurgling, halitosis and recurrent aspiration events. In severe cases, malnutrition and weight loss may be evident. This patient has presented with several of these symptoms. His lateral chest x-ray demonstrates an air-fluid level at the thoracic inlet. This is a large pharyngeal pouch (Zenker diverticulum).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst a \u003Cstrong\u003Epara-oesphageal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E might explain some of his symptoms, there is no evidence of one on the x-ray. This type of hernia would be shown as an air-fluid level immediately above the diaphragm. Symptoms of para-ooesophageal hernias are most often related to oesophageal reflux and regurgitation, as opposed to dysphagia. Patients may also complain of nausea and vomiting, as well as increasing breathlessness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the mid-third of the oesophagu\u003C/strong\u003Es is not the best answer. A lateral chest x-ray will seldom detect oesophageal cancer. Furthermore, patients are more likely to present with progressive dysphagia, first to solids and then to liquids. It does not generally cause gurgling. Patients are also likely to present with weight loss, although as already discussed, this cannot be used to reliably distinguish between a pharyngeal pouch and oesophageal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ESchatzski ring\u003C/strong\u003E is a narrowing of the distal oesophagus (generally at the gastro-oesophageal junction). Patients will present with intermittent episodes of dysphagia, particularly to solid foods. In this case, the x-ray demonstrates the abnormality to be located more proximally than the gastro-oesophageal junction, making Schatzski ring an incorrect answer option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eretrosternal goitre\u003C/strong\u003E will often cause dysphagia to solids, as well as breathlessness on exertion and a postive Pemberton\u0027s sign (due to thoracic inlet obstruction). An obvious neck swelling would usually be present and an X-ray will often demonstrate a large mass in the superior mediastinum, reflecting the location of the enlarged thyroid gland. There is no evidence of these features here, aside from the dyshagia. As such, a retrosternal goitre is not the best answer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Common causes of dysphagia and radiographic findings"],"references":["Law R, Katzka DA, Baron TH. Zenker\u2019s diverticulum. Clinical Gastroenterology and Hepatology. 2014 Nov;12(11):1773\u201382"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43977"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1647"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18349"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21120"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18349","links":{